            }
        }
    }

The main challenge in this problem is allowing a particular element to be picked up more than once.

So, the idea (in the above code) is to keep moving forward on each recursive call. In your code, each recursive call started at the element at index 0, which was the reason to that led to duplicates. Here, each recursive calls starts at the element at index `pos`. 

To pick a particular element more than once, we check how many of it (the current element) can contribute to the overall (remaining) target by checking `(target - sum) / candidates[i]` (let this be `ct`). So, we make recursive calls by picking *1, 2, 3... ct* of them (adding to the current sum).

Some points:

1. To avoid mutating the array, I create new ones to simplify the code. You can change it if it proves to be affecting the performance.
2. I have kept `finalOutput` as a static variable. You can pass it as a parameter.

